-- ===== PART 4: COMMUNITY AND INVESTMENT MAP =====
($KB$Community selection: how to evaluate any area$KB$, $KB$Founder's Knowledge$KB$,
$KB$Founder view: never recommend a community blindly. First understand whether it is mature, early-stage, end-user, rental-yield, capital-appreciation, luxury, waterfront, family-focused, overpriced, under- or over-supplied, or only worth it on a strong resale deal. Before recommending any area, check developer, entry price, price per square foot, payment plan, handover, current resale and rental demand, service charges, future supply, community maturity, connectivity, end-user appeal and the client's objective. Agent rule: do not sell the area - sell the logic. Every recommendation must have a reason. Investment status language to use: Buy / Hold / End-user / Avoid / Only if below OP / Only if resale deal.$KB$,
$KB$community, area, evaluate, investment status, entry price, price per sqft, supply, service charges, maturity, connectivity, how to choose area$KB$,
'all','active',2,'Founder KB v2 (Market, Developer, Community)'),

($KB$Waterfront communities map (Palm Jebel Ali, Dubai Islands, City seaside)$KB$, $KB$Founder's Knowledge$KB$,
$KB$Founder waterfront map. Palm Jebel Ali (Nakheel) - a grand, newer, larger, more refined long-term waterfront plan (luxury, beach and coral villas); view it long-term, not as a flip; best for patient long-term, luxury, Golden Visa and lifestyle buyers. Frame it as a long-term waterfront scarcity play - do NOT say it will definitely become the next Palm Jumeirah. Dubai Islands (Nakheel) - closer to the city with more advanced infrastructure, so potentially shorter-term results than Palm Jebel Ali; Nakheel-led parts (townhouses, villas, mansions, residences) can be strong; study Bay Grove Residences, Rixos Residences, and Ellington and Beyond projects; good for buyers who missed Palm Jumeirah. Jumeirah Bay (Meraas) - super-prime trophy market now (Bvlgari); the big investment entry was earlier. Bluewaters (Meraas) - limited supply; major appreciation already happened, now lifestyle and scarcity. La Mer / Port de La Mer (Meraas) - now more end-user; J1 Beach adds lifestyle. Emaar Beachfront - strong earlier window; be selective now. Rashid Yachts and Marina (Emaar) - some attractive resale; mid-to-long-term waterfront. Dubai Creek Harbour (Emaar) - a mix of Downtown and Marina; mid-to-long-term, not a quick flip. Note: freehold supply on the seaside of Sheikh Zayed Road is limited - scarcity supports long-term demand when entry price is fair.$KB$,
$KB$waterfront, palm jebel ali, dubai islands, jumeirah bay, bluewaters, la mer, port de la mer, emaar beachfront, rashid yachts and marina, dubai creek harbour, nakheel, meraas, sheikh zayed road, seaside, scarcity, bay grove, rixos, ellington, beyond$KB$,
'all','active',2,'Founder KB v2 (Market, Developer, Community)'),

($KB$Central and lifestyle communities (Downtown, Business Bay, City Walk, D3, DIFC)$KB$, $KB$Founder's Knowledge$KB$,
$KB$Founder central and lifestyle map. Downtown Dubai (mostly Emaar, mature) - iconic prestige and rental/lifestyle address; capital appreciation is now slower because it is mature; best for end-users, luxury living, prestige and long-term holding, not the fastest growth play. Business Bay - very mixed (ultra-luxury towers alongside average private-developer ones); BE CAREFUL - some private developers price towers high by saying next to Downtown, sometimes above good Downtown resale; never recommend blindly - check developer, price per square foot, exact location, view, service charges, building quality and resale comparables, and whether the price is justified. Dubai Marina - mature, strong rental and lifestyle, slower growth. City Walk (Meraas) - chic, low-rise, central, very strong for rentals due to limited supply and a unique lifestyle (can beat Downtown on rentals); strong mid-to-long-term, not short-term flipping; Central Park added a major residential phase; Crestlane at City Walk is a newer low and mid-rise concept toward Al Wasl Road with potential skyline and sea views. Dubai Design District / D3 (Meraas) - strong rental story: high office and professional demand, limited residential supply, central, with a waterfront component (study Design Quarter). DIFC - interesting mid-to-long-term: financial institutions, hedge funds and family offices create strong executive tenant demand.$KB$,
$KB$downtown, business bay, dubai marina, city walk, crestlane, central park, dubai design district, d3, difc, rental, lifestyle, meraas, emaar, central, office demand$KB$,
'all','active',2,'Founder KB v2 (Market, Developer, Community)'),

($KB$Family, villa and townhouse communities map$KB$, $KB$Founder's Knowledge$KB$,
$KB$Founder family map. Dubai Hills Estate (Emaar) - strong central family community (villas, townhouses, golf, mall, schools); good resale apartment deals can be attractive if the entry price is right. The Valley (Emaar) - family-focused; the best angle is resale (3-4 bedroom townhouses or larger-plot Farm Gardens villas) at a fair price. The Oasis (Emaar) - lagoon and luxury villas; look for early-phase resale at OP or below. Arabian Ranches 1 and 2 - mature, mainly end-user; AR3 may have limited near-handover opportunities only if priced well versus ready. Nad Al Sheba Gardens - villas and townhouses close to Downtown, DIFC, Meydan, MBR City and District One; attractive if you find a good deal - entry price is the key. Dubai South - long-term infrastructure play (Al Maktoum airport); townhouses and villas usually better than apartments. Expo City - interesting if the payment plan is strong (e.g. post-handover) - verify current plans. Tilal Al Ghaf (Majid Al Futtaim) - excellent when bought early (Elan, Harmony, Aura, Alaya, Serenity); now more end-user unless a strong resale deal appears. Jumeirah Park and Jumeirah Islands - mature family villa communities, good for end-use and long-term holding, not fast appreciation.$KB$,
$KB$dubai hills, the valley, the oasis, arabian ranches, nad al sheba gardens, meydan, mbr city, district one, dubai south, expo city, tilal al ghaf, jumeirah park, jumeirah islands, family, villa, townhouse, emaar, majid al futtaim, resale$KB$,
'all','active',2,'Founder KB v2 (Market, Developer, Community)'),

($KB$Mid-tier and caution areas (be price-disciplined)$KB$, $KB$Founder's Knowledge$KB$,
$KB$Founder caution map - be price-disciplined. JVC and JVT - mid to lower tier, heavily supplied with private-developer apartments; work only if the entry price is very strong; risky for capital appreciation. Sobha Hartland - good quality but can be overpriced for investment; better for end-users; check entry price. Town Square - not high-end; prices have already moved a lot; be cautious and prefer better alternatives. Dubai Sports City and Motor City - mostly mature and end-user, not high-end; price-driven yield plays only. Al Furjan - mostly mature; good end-user and rental depending on project and price; investment must be project-specific. JLT - mature; strong rental in selected towers; slower growth. Dubai Silicon Oasis - mature and end-user; limited upside unless entry price is very strong. Damac Hills - mature, better for end-use. Damac Lagoons - only if a very good townhouse resale deal. Rule: never recommend Damac or any of these blindly - check price, phase, payment remaining, resale comparables, handover and demand.$KB$,
